Step 4: Determine which ablation results in the largest relative improvement. Since all ablated models have higher LPIPS scores than the Full Model, they represent a degradation in performance. Therefore, none of the ablations result in an improvement. However, if we interpret "largest relative improvement" as the smallest increase in LPIPS (i.e., the least degradation), we look for the ablation that has the smallest increase from the Full Model.

The smallest increase is for "w/o motion pre-training" (0.149 - 0.126 = 0.023), followed by "w/o multi-motion joint training" (0.151 - 0.126 = 0.025), "w/o latent space" (0.163 - 0.126 = 0.037), and "w/o motion factorization" (0.154 - 0.126 = 0.028).

