Step 2: Understand the implications of these variants.
SVLTrack-L uses only natural language descriptions (no bounding boxes), which is a form of weak supervision. SVLTrack-V uses only initial bounding boxes (no language). The paper's goal is to achieve self-supervised tracking without any bounding-box ground truth, so these variants represent different approaches to achieving that goal.

Step 3: Analyze the trade-offs.
The key trade-off is between the richness of the initialization signal (language vs. bounding box) and the feasibility of training without any human annotations. Natural language descriptions are more informative about the target object (e.g., "white horse walking in the field"), but they require human input. Bounding boxes are less informative but do not require human input beyond the initial frame. Therefore, the trade-off is between the quality of the initial signal (richness) and the ease of obtaining it (annotation-free).

Step 4: Evaluate the options.
Option A is incorrect because the paper doesn't discuss computational cost or inference speed.
Option C is incorrect because while SVLTrack-V384 runs at 56 FPS, this is a performance metric, not a fundamental trade-off discussed in the context of the variants' design.
Option D is incorrect because the paper doesn't mention training data diversity as a factor.
Option B correctly identifies the trade-off between initialization signal richness (natural language being more informative) and annotation-free training feasibility (natural language requires human input, bounding boxes don't).

